It was an overwhelming success. Audiences showed up for every stop of her tour and she sold out every venue she performed in. This tour paved the way for Arab artists to more confidently tour the United States  with the knowledge that the diaspora audience was willing to show up.

Fairuz's tour to the US in 1971 was a risk because the numbers amounted to a marginal profit, if even that. However, the Rahbani team decided to take a chance on touring the U.S. anyway, believing that the Arab diaspora there is big enough that it warranted a try.

There was always fear that unless a singer achieves significant international success, like Oum Kalthoum, a tour outside of Latin America, which has a significant Arab diaspora population, or the Middle East, would not be worth the expenses.

There's not much to really say about this concert but it's significant in that it was one of the few times that an Arab singer toured outside the Middle East and Latin America, very few were given this privilege: Oum Kalthoum, Sabah, come to mind.
